WEBVTT

1
00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:39.460
Welcome, everybody, some gentle tones.

2
00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:50.400
That was the xylophone that was used for ABC radio very few years ago, when this was the ABC radio studio.

3
00:00:52.540 --> 00:00:57.280
You would have woken up to that from a certain vintage.

4
00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:05.560
So welcome, everyone, to the inaugural Basil's Table.

5
00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:16.580
I'd firstly like to start by acknowledging the righty people of the Kulin Nation, and I pay my respects to their elders past and present.

6
00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:27.980
And in particular, I'd like to mention the very many indigenous and Aboriginal cooperatives across the state, many of which go under the radar.

7
00:01:27.980 --> 00:01:32.940
And I think there's a great opportunity with the cooperative movement to make links.

8
00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:36.900
The sixth principle of cooperatives is cooperation amongst cooperatives.

9
00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:53.620
So I think that's something that we can all sort of focus on in terms of our duty to support reconciliation, restitution and all those sorts of things that we need to think about.

10
00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:57.060
My name is Antony.

11
00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:02.900
I'm the chair of the 888 Co-operative causeway Limited.

12
00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:05.740
Who thought of that?

13
00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:05.840
No.

14
00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:16.160
The idea is 888 is a balance between work and recreation and rest.

15
00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.740
Co-operative is about the relationship that we have with each other.

16
00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:29.620
We're working towards the common good, which is the causeway, which is our little headquarters, which is just down the road.

17
00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:37.380
So our little cooperative has a cooperative desk space, and our cooperative is a member of this club, is a corporate member.

18
00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:43.580
So this is how we can run events right here as we have it tonight.

19
00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:44.560
But this is a bit different.

20
00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.720
We're trying something a bit different tonight.

21
00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:54.380
So the theme tonight is banking on the future in a climate of change.

22
00:02:54.380 --> 00:03:02.700
obviously, in australia, we've been through a very difficult time as a country in terms of the tragic bushfires.

23
00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:12.440
And it's a time where it's sometimes difficult to hold some hope or optimism or something that, you know, something creative.

24
00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:26.520
So the idea behind this series of discussions is to actually talk to people who are doing good stuff, both seasoned and emerging, and make links between people and come along.

25
00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:33.420
So that's why we started off with a bit of food and a drink and introducing ourselves to each other and building links.

26
00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:37.480
And often that's a value as well of going to an event like this.

27
00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:48.440
So in 1996, a quarter of all australians were members of what was then called a credit union.

28
00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:51.760
So you still get credit unions, you still get building societies.

29
00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:57.560
Often now they're called customer-owned banks, but they're all the same thing.

30
00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:02.100
It's where members have an ownership stake.

31
00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:16.440
Today, fast forward, I don't know what the proportion of customer-owned or member-owned financial institutions are of this figure, but eight out of 10 of us are members of a cooperative or a mutual.

32
00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:20.680
A lot of us don't know that, but I reckon most people here would.

33
00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:23.340
It's like a pretty educated world.

34
00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:26.900
So you probably know that stat already, I reckon.

35
00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:45.140
So in 1996, historian Gary Lewis, who recently passed away, had some interesting observations to make about credit unions.

36
00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:51.240
And I thought I'd kick things off before introducing our speakers with a couple of his observations.

37
00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:02.120
And I've just gotten to that age, you know, I'm in my 40s and now I'm finding, you know how you still look at people and they go like this?

38
00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:05.660
And suddenly, it's only the last year.

39
00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:07.040
So I'm just getting on top.

40
00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:09.860
A few years.

41
00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:13.340
All right.

42
00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:36.060
Since the Second World War, australian credit unions have defeated usury, pioneered innovative financial services, improved competition in and moulded the shape of the finance industry and broadened the democratization of wealth.

43
00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:48.940
They have demonstrated that ordinary people, cooperating to meet their financial needs, employing appropriate technology and expertise, can achieve quite remarkable economic outcomes.

44
00:05:50.960 --> 00:06:03.720
This study, this book, shows the ability of credit unions to apply unorthodox democratic remedies to problems that would normally cripple other businesses.

45
00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:16.220
australian credit unions first include loan protection insurance at no extra cost, free direct payroll deductions for members.

46
00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.360
The first ATMs were in a credit union.

47
00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:23.720
EFTPOS came out of the credit union movement in australia.

48
00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:30.600
The first international visa ATM withdrawal in the world came out of the credit union movement in 1984.

49
00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:34.880
Telephone activated home banking services.

50
00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:38.680
That's why I remember using that when I joined Endeavour Credit Union back in the day.

51
00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:44.040
You'd ring up and you'd use your touch tone and you'd be able to move money across and all that.

52
00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:45.500
It was very, very innovative.

53
00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:48.580
You probably still can do that in some quarters.

54
00:06:51.360 --> 00:07:01.460
Credit unions have been at the forefront of providing value and things like the chip card was a first for credit unions.

55
00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:07.360
The largest providers of personal loans and visa debt cards in australia when this book was written.

56
00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:08.480
That was then.

57
00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:13.840
At the moment, we've got a lot of innovation happening with start up banks.

58
00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:14.580
They're a platform.

59
00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:20.220
I heard on the radio a particular start up platform type of bank had...

60
00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:22.200
They said, Oh, yeah, we can give these great interest rates.

61
00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:25.380
And then I asked about how many people they employ.

62
00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:27.760
And, you know, it was very low.

63
00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:32.840
It's like 40 or 50 people employed by this new sort of start up bank.

64
00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:34.540
So there is innovation going out there.

65
00:07:34.540 --> 00:07:38.780
And it'd be interesting to hear from our speaker about what's happening in that area.

66
00:07:38.780 --> 00:07:57.700
But the purpose of tonight really is to go a little deeper than the day to day, to go a little bit about why people get involved in this area that we call the social economy, why people would get involved in credit unions or housing co-ops and various things like that.

67
00:07:57.720 --> 00:08:02.780
And again, in this history book, I found something that I just thought I would mention.

68
00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:09.400
Is it an acrostic when you say the words and each word has a thing?

69
00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:10.400
It's like an acrostic.

70
00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:11.020
My kids do it.

71
00:08:11.020 --> 00:08:12.320
I think that's an acrostic, isn't it?

72
00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:14.500
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

73
00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:16.120
Mutual aid.

74
00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:22.700
Now, this was in 1956 by the Young Christian Workers, who are a big part of the Whole Credit Union movement.

75
00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:25.600
Mutual aid.

76
00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:27.560
Money when you need it.

77
00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:51.120
Under easy repayment terms, training in thrift, United Fund of Members Savings, available for loans, low interest rates, aid to lessor financial worry, independence from exploitation, deposit interest better than bank.

78
00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:53.920
And so hopefully that's still the case.

79
00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.280
Mutual aid.

80
00:08:57.520 --> 00:08:59.680
Now, again, I'm struggling.

81
00:08:59.680 --> 00:09:01.020
I really need glasses.

82
00:09:01.020 --> 00:09:05.960
Okay, but I would actually like to get to the most important part, which is introducing these two people.

83
00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:10.780
So we have Basil and his table.

84
00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:15.160
And we have Rowan Dowland from Bank australia.

85
00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:22.100
So Basil, you would have read the bio in the promotional material.

86
00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:29.580
My relationship with Basil started when he taught me community development back in the day in the 90s.

87
00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:31.080
And we kept that up.

88
00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:39.000
And he's been someone that's committed himself to community development, development of community over many, many years.

89
00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.820
So he is bringing that experience along tonight.

90
00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:49.040
Rowan Dowland heads up strategy and planning at Bank australia.

91
00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:55.120
So I assume he's got the telescope out at times and is looking out.

92
00:09:55.120 --> 00:10:05.000
But tonight we're going to also look a little bit inwards and seeing what this social economy leader has to say about his commitment to his work.

93
00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:15.280
So without further ado, I'm going to hand the mic over and we're going to start the Basil's Table.

94
00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:23.560
I've got a microphone here.

95
00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:34.660
Well, thank you, Antony, for that introduction, and thank you all those people who have come here today, which is wonderful.

96
00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:38.760
So thank you, those people that I do know, and those that I'm going to get to know.

97
00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:41.800
I really appreciate the fact that you have come here.

98
00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:43.380
This is...

99
00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:46.380
just good to take a ride.

100
00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:55.100
Hello?

101
00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:55.780
Yeah.

102
00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:56.740
Did you hear me before?

103
00:10:56.740 --> 00:10:57.940
I will go to repeat that.

104
00:10:57.940 --> 00:10:59.300
No.

105
00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:09.140
And it's actually a great honor and privilege here to be with Rowan, whom I, we have actually had two conversations.

106
00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:25.660
And he is a very impressive man who has committed himself really to an area of life that I am not all that familiar with, because I, when it comes to money, I'm hopeless.

107
00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:33.680
As a matter of fact, friends who know me know that I'm actually just terrible when it comes to money management.

108
00:11:33.680 --> 00:11:41.960
And yet, I do know that money has been useful, as to quote someone famous, tainted as it is.

109
00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:45.640
It actually is important to get things done.

110
00:11:47.220 --> 00:12:03.320
So, I've now got more and more involved, mainly because of Antony, with the 888, and understand that we really need to get our heads around the whole aspect of profit.

111
00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:11.180
And we also have to get our heads around the importance of what is it to be not greedy.

112
00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:12.760
But I'll elaborate on that later.

113
00:12:13.560 --> 00:12:17.400
Well, I'd like to now ask Rowan, because we have this thing.

114
00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:19.720
Should you have the first question or should I have the first question?

115
00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:28.780
Now, I decided, you're my guest or our guest, you should actually be the person who actually responds to my question.

116
00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:31.260
We flip these backwards and forwards so many times.

117
00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:33.860
But hopefully, we will dial it.

118
00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:48.820
So, in terms of the question here, what is it about corporatives that attracted you to one and caused you to stay for the past 25 years or so?

119
00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:53.940
Thanks, Basil, and thanks for the introduction as well, Antony.

120
00:12:54.600 --> 00:13:00.080
The book that Antony referred to tonight, there's only two copies of it in australia, I understand.

121
00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:04.220
No, Antony's got one and I've got one.

122
00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:06.700
You've got one as well, there's three.

123
00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:08.000
Fantastic.

124
00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:16.360
I was given a copy of this book on the very first day that I joined our credit union, which was the SEC credit union.

125
00:13:16.360 --> 00:13:17.820
Some of you may remember that at the time.

126
00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:23.320
It was the largest GELD SEC, cracking how things change in Victoria.

127
00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:27.860
I still carry my copy around and I still referred to it.

128
00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:36.600
I'm talking to new staff who join the now a bank, customer-owned cooperative bank.

129
00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:45.940
Absolutely by coincidence, the paragraph that you read out tonight is one of the paragraphs that I share with all new people coming to join the bank.

130
00:13:46.040 --> 00:14:03.020
because I just think it's so critically important that as we're building banks for the future, we never forget our past and we never forget our legacy and we never forget those people, those pioneers, those people who were brave and bold, who had the courage to actually form a cooperative or credit union movement in australia.

131
00:14:03.020 --> 00:14:17.900
If we lose sight of the values that the bravery, the sense of purpose that our founders had in australia, then I think we actually lose something from our culture and our DNA.

132
00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:25.160
So, Basil, why did I join the cooperative movement, which is over 28 years ago?

133
00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.560
I don't know a lot about money either, I've got to tell you.

134
00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.960
I'm not a banker at all.

135
00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:39.200
But there is a driving hypothesis, I guess, that I've been trying to prove throughout my life.

136
00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:45.520
And my career started within the property industry here in Melbourne, in the real estate industry.

137
00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:59.800
From a very young boy, I always wanted to be in the property industry, real estate industry, and I was offered the opportunity to study and do a cadetship in those days with one of the largest real estate firms here in Melbourne.

138
00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:16.500
But within a very, very short period of time, I realized that my values were not aligned to the values of the property industry, which were all about individuals, commission driven individuals, seeking to acquire wealth without having a sense of community.

139
00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:19.400
It was about, I win when you lose.

140
00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:26.600
And I stayed within that industry for four years and then took an about base, 180 degree turn.

141
00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:54.800
And went from quite a privileged career and position in the real estate industry and joined the Ministry of housing here, working with homeless people across Melbourne and working with women's refuges, working with the Gill Memorial and other institutions that were providing housing and accommodation to homeless people and worked within both the government housing sector and the community housing sector for about 10 years in total.

142
00:15:54.800 --> 00:16:19.520
My next move was to try and find a business model that combined the commercial discipline of running a business together with the experience of the things, the aspects that I liked of the government and community sector, which was a real strong sense of social purpose and social justice and existing for the purpose of enhancing the quality of people and their lives in a strong sense of community.

143
00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:27.680
And my mum had been a teacher and she was a member of one of the teacher based credit unions here in Melbourne.

144
00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:31.400
And she was what was called in those days a member rep that they had.

145
00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:34.040
And so in fact, I'd never been a customer of a bank.

146
00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:36.520
I'd only ever been a member of a credit union.

147
00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:50.600
So I thought I would try the experience of joining a credit union here in Melbourne and join the SEC credit union, which at the time was the largest credit union here in Victoria.

148
00:16:50.600 --> 00:16:55.260
And my sense was that the model had enormous opportunity.

149
00:16:55.260 --> 00:16:59.600
I think there was a period of time with credit unions where they lost their way.

150
00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:01.240
They lost a sense of purpose.

151
00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:14.420
But I believe strongly in the cooperative model, both and looked internationally at the strength of the cooperative model, not just in banking, but across a broad range of industries and sectors.

152
00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:23.760
And I believe that if we could build a strong cooperative and align with a strong sense of purpose, then we could create a sustainable business model.

153
00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:25.680
And that's going back into the 90s.

154
00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:29.120
And I've been in the industry now for 28 years.

155
00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:36.000
We've built a credit union myself and my colleagues have built a credit union into australia's first cooperative bank.

156
00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:42.800
Those that are not familiar with Bank australia, we became the first cooperative bank in australia in 2011.

157
00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:48.960
In Europe, cooperative banks, take a country like Germany.

158
00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:52.220
Germany's banking system is clearly very significant.

159
00:17:55.060 --> 00:17:59.780
Banking industry, about 45% of banking in Germany is done through cooperative banks.

160
00:17:59.780 --> 00:18:06.740
And it kind of always intrigued me that you can have such strong cooperative banks in other parts of the world, particularly Europe, but less so here.

161
00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:13.000
And one of the ambitions that we did have was to establish australia's first cooperative bank, which we did in 2011.

162
00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.400
In 2015, we renamed that bank, Bank australia.

163
00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:23.360
And ever since doing that, we've been growing the business very, very strong and very successfully.

164
00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:32.300
But it hasn't always been enough challenges and enough opportunities over that period of time to keep me engaged in the business.

165
00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:36.960
And we had lost our way in the late 90s.

166
00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:39.640
In fact, let me just tell you the story very briefly.

167
00:18:40.820 --> 00:18:45.340
At that time, I believe it was essential to build scale within credit unions.

168
00:18:45.340 --> 00:18:49.000
So when I started, it was a 50 million, we managed $50 million in assets.

169
00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.380
Today, we manage around $7 billion in assets.

170
00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:54.780
And we would still be describing ourselves as sub-scale.

171
00:18:54.780 --> 00:19:02.340
So as part of the way of being able to build scale in the 90s, we acquired a number of credit unions, smaller credit unions.

172
00:19:02.340 --> 00:19:03.560
We brought them into the group.

173
00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:10.460
So whilst I started in the SEC credit union, I also worked in the ANSET credit union and the David Syme credit union.

174
00:19:10.460 --> 00:19:14.580
We acquired the CSIRO staff credit union and a number of other credit unions.

175
00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:20.740
And in fact, today, there's some 72 credit unions that form the Bank australia group.

176
00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:37.020
But what we discovered in late 90s was that without a strong sense of purpose, then you can lose your way very quickly and you can become quite irrelevant to the customers that own either the credit union or the bank.

177
00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:40.760
And I remember listening in on a conversation down in the Latrobe Valley.

178
00:19:40.760 --> 00:19:44.520
We have a business in the Latrobe Valley based off the SEC days.

179
00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:50.480
And I remember listening to callers coming into the call center and they were saying things like, you guys have just got bigger, but you've not got better.

180
00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:53.360
I don't understand why you exist any longer.

181
00:19:53.360 --> 00:20:04.080
I understood the purpose behind the credit union as a scientist with the CSIRO or a pilot with ANTCEP or someone, an editor at David Syme.

182
00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:21.240
You represented a banking opportunity or banking option for people that could associate, could identify with a defined group, a defined community, and you are no longer the staff credit unit, the pilots or empower workers.

183
00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:24.300
I don't understand it anymore.

184
00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:28.360
I sat down with the CEO at the time and said, I think we're actually in strife here.

185
00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:34.100
We've been building this business and today, and at that point in time, we're probably 650 million dollars in assets.

186
00:20:34.100 --> 00:20:42.300
We were growing, we were existing as opposed to having a strong sense of understanding why we existed and the purpose behind why we existed.

187
00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:45.200
John at the time said, look, you're right.

188
00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:53.560
This is not a way to build this business if we can't define, articulate our strong sense of purpose.

189
00:20:53.560 --> 00:21:02.880
You go and spend a few months spending time with cooperatives around the world, to try and understand what it is that makes those businesses successful.

190
00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:07.320
I came back in australia after a number of months and said, I think I've discovered it.

191
00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:15.540
Now, what we've been doing as we've been building this business, we lost sight of a strong sense of purpose.

192
00:21:15.540 --> 00:21:22.980
People could no longer identify with the business and we've defined the business according historically according to jobs or geography.

193
00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:24.420
That's how the credit unions were.

194
00:21:24.420 --> 00:21:30.840
They were the industry based credit unions, they were parish based credit unions or they were community based credit unions defined by geography.

195
00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:34.660
I said the future is no longer jobs or geography or vocation or location.

196
00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:40.860
The future of cooperatives in banking and our cooperative was attitudes and values.

197
00:21:40.860 --> 00:21:43.160
It's what people believe.

198
00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:57.180
If people believe in a strong sense of community, if people believe that we as a business can help and power them to use their monies in ways that create strong social, environmental, cultural and economic impact.

199
00:21:57.180 --> 00:22:12.020
If we can use money in a way that enhances their lives, enhances the lives of others, and improves the quality of life that we exist in terms of the planet and the environment, then I think we've defined a new space in the australian banking sector.

200
00:22:12.020 --> 00:22:14.020
That's what we did in 2002.

201
00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:26.740
We put a merger together that gives a bit more scale, but on the basis of saying, we're going to be a business that now defines its purpose, not according to jobs and geography, but according to the old traditional credit union values.

202
00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:42.720
You bring a community of interests together, and through that community of interests, now defined by our attitudes and values, not jobs and geography, we're going to get those people to save together, and we're going to invest those monies in ways that improve the quality of their lives, the lives of others and the planet.

203
00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:52.640
We're going to use that money in ways that make a positive impact in the community, in the world, around the issues that are important to them.

204
00:22:53.020 --> 00:23:03.580
What I really love about that is that it is completely consistent with the principles, the philosophies, the values that underpin cooperatives, banks that were formed in Germany in the mid 1800s.

205
00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:12.380
So they brought together groups of artisans and farmers who were unbanked, said, let's save together and let's provide an opportunity for these communities to bank.

206
00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:14.380
And we're doing exactly the same today.

207
00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:18.860
The issues change for our customers, and that's the exciting part.

208
00:23:18.860 --> 00:23:21.980
That's the thing that keeps us quite dynamic.

209
00:23:21.980 --> 00:23:26.540
We say these days that we need to be a good bank because you can't trade off values.

210
00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:29.140
You need to be a good bank and a force for good.

211
00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:35.680
You need to be able to compete with banking product and services and technology and all the things that Anthony referred to, Visa cards and the like.

212
00:23:35.680 --> 00:23:38.700
But none of that's going to differentiate us in the marketplace.

213
00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:42.440
It's being a force for good that differentiates us in the marketplace.

214
00:23:42.540 --> 00:23:46.740
So we know from our customers the things that are important to them.

215
00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:53.160
We know that the number one issue that's important to our customers at the moment is climate change, the future of the planet.

216
00:23:53.160 --> 00:24:03.020
And we know that if we can align their money, invest their money in ways that create positive environmental impact, then we're meeting our purpose, we're meeting our needs as a cooperative.

217
00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:15.920
And at any one time we know the 10 or 11 most important issues that are important to our customers, climate change, renewable energy, fair treatment of refugees, closing the gap on indigenous mental health issues, homelessness, house affordability.

218
00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:17.700
We know what those issues are.

219
00:24:17.700 --> 00:24:26.840
And we continue to align the business of banking to those issues and invest our customers' money in ways that have positive impacts in those areas.

220
00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:29.260
And I've been doing it for 28 years.

221
00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:37.820
I can share with you that last month, so the business is now 62 years old, as I said, manages about $7 billion in assets.

222
00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:43.640
Last year, we attracted more people into the bank than any other month in the past 62 years.

223
00:24:45.340 --> 00:24:55.240
Purely on the basis of the principles that underpinned the cooperative when we formed it in 1957 and the same principles that underpinned cooperatives when they were formed in the 1850s.

224
00:24:56.880 --> 00:25:01.520
Providing a values-based or values-led approach to banking.

225
00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:18.660
The vast majority of people who joined us last month, record number, almost 4,000 people joined us, switched out of the four major banks to join Bank australia last month, joined us because they wanted to empower themselves in a way that helped make a positive difference on climate change.

226
00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:24.940
It was the fires that occurred throughout the summer period where people said, I need to do something here.

227
00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:26.680
We can see that, we can track that throughout the year.

228
00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:30.880
We know there's a campaign about to be launched around animal exports.

229
00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:32.980
We have a strong position on animal exports.

230
00:25:33.060 --> 00:25:34.600
You may have seen some of our advertising.

231
00:25:34.600 --> 00:25:37.500
The things we do, do the things we don't do.

232
00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:59.740
And as the community becomes aware and more aware that they can empower themselves in ways that bring about positive changes, simply through the way they invest their money, they bank their everyday banking, we've seen influx of business coming into the Bank australia based purely on a strong sense of purpose, based purely on a strong sense of cooperative values.

233
00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:09.260
And that's what keeps me here now after 28, almost 30 years, and I'm kind of getting towards the end of my career and bringing on the next generation of people to take the business forward.

234
00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:18.600
But what I'm hoping that they learn either from myself and my experience or reading the book is that the principles of being a cooperative still stand true today.

235
00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:20.740
They've stood the test of time.

236
00:26:20.740 --> 00:26:26.500
They are as relevant today as they were in the 1850s, as they were in 1957 when we were born.

237
00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:32.380
And they can still capture the imagination of people.

238
00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:40.120
And to get 4,000 people, when I look at the 4,000 people who joined us in January, the average age was 34.

239
00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:41.880
What?

240
00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:42.620
That's amazing.

241
00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:46.920
None of them, well, none, I won't say none.

242
00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:55.240
Something in the order of about 87% of them did not factor price into their decision to switch out of one of the full major banks to Bank australia.

243
00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:59.980
Whilst we would never trade away price, price is critically important of being cooperative.

244
00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:09.360
They joined us because of principles and values and a strong sense of I want to, I want my money to have a positive impact in the world.

245
00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:14.100
Now people used to say to me banks can only compete on price.

246
00:27:14.100 --> 00:27:17.060
And I said we would never trade price away.

247
00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:30.680
But banks can compete on purpose and you can define a space for a cooperative bank in the marketplace simply by meeting people's expectations around doing good in the world as opposed to doing harm in the world.

248
00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:34.140
That's a really long answer to your question.

249
00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:35.800
But I've been at it for 28 years.

250
00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:43.240
And I kind of, as committed to it today, now the only reason why I'll step out of the business is because I've kind of hit retirement.

251
00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:51.420
It's not because I'm any less committed to the purpose of the bank today than I was 28 years ago.

252
00:27:51.420 --> 00:27:59.300
And when you see 4,000 people join the bank in January, and this month it's probably over, it'll be over 3,000.

253
00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:02.700
And again, the average age is going to be somewhere around about 34, 35.

254
00:28:03.200 --> 00:28:08.580
And they're empowering themselves to bring about positive change in the world.

255
00:28:08.580 --> 00:28:09.740
That's incredibly cool.

256
00:28:09.740 --> 00:28:20.740
For somebody who kind of, you know, all those years ago wanted to test the hypothesis of can a business exist for a purpose beyond profit maximization, I think we're about to give ourselves a tick.

257
00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:25.920
Thank you.

258
00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:37.260
The other amazing part about that is that our brand has only been in the market place really since 2017.

259
00:28:37.260 --> 00:28:38.320
So it's a very new brand.

260
00:28:38.320 --> 00:28:44.560
Whilst the business has been operated under all these different names for some years, it's really only been known from Bank australia since 2017.

261
00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:55.060
And in the last week, we appeared as number 42 in australia's most trusted brands, which gives me&#8230;

262
00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:56.900
The meaning of life, really.

263
00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:02.580
I just think, no, banks have lost people's trust.

264
00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:03.880
That's why we had a Royal Commission.

265
00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:29.380
So, within three years to be in the top number 42 and top 50 most trusted brands in australia, that gives me great hope that the people who will take over from me, who will be younger and smarter and more, they have got an amazing future to take that business up for three years from being the 42nd most trusted brand in the country to number one, all based on values.

266
00:29:30.860 --> 00:29:39.440
That's for people who understand the value of co-operatives and understand the value of co-operative values.

267
00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:44.560
I think that just is something, and many of us have been beating the drum for that for many years.

268
00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:46.320
Their future is incredible.

269
00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:56.000
Well, it's interesting that none of the credit unions or the banks had to appear for the Royal Commission, while all the others had to.

270
00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:01.040
Not a single co-operative or mutual bank appeared before the Royal Commission.

271
00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:05.700
We all wrote submissions, but we didn't appear before.

272
00:30:05.700 --> 00:30:12.660
The Royal Commission was not called because of the business practices of the co-operative or mutual banks in the country.

273
00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:17.380
We know why it was called.

274
00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:23.840
We sit, it's interesting, as a very small bank, we sit at the table of the australian Bankers Association.

275
00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:25.960
Some people say, why would you do that?

276
00:30:25.960 --> 00:30:31.920
Why would you sit in the same room as all the other investor owned banks in the country?

277
00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:36.540
We're part of a global alliance for banking on values.

278
00:30:36.540 --> 00:30:44.300
And part of our commitment as being a member of the global alliance is that we try and influence banking, try to influence the banking sector.

279
00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:47.360
So we believe we have a responsibility to sit at the table.

280
00:30:47.460 --> 00:30:48.340
It's kind of interesting.

281
00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:51.160
We're the tiniest member of the ABA.

282
00:30:51.160 --> 00:30:56.700
You're sitting at the table and there's the CEOs and deputy CEOs of all the largest banks in the country.

283
00:30:57.900 --> 00:31:03.100
It's a bit like when I was a kid, the naughty boys used to sit on the car table at the end of the dining table.

284
00:31:03.100 --> 00:31:05.080
Well, we're kind of the odd one out.

285
00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:06.660
We always sit at the end of the table.

286
00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:09.440
We're the big guys at one end and we're at the other end.

287
00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:15.760
So we understand we were very close to the decisions around why Royal Commission was called.

288
00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:18.340
And we understood what the practices were.

289
00:31:19.500 --> 00:31:26.280
And we take great pride in the fact that there was no mutual cooperative bank that was part of the Royal Commission.

290
00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:27.720
Why was the Royal Commission called?

291
00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:32.400
The Royal Commission was called for one simple reason, in our sense.

292
00:31:32.400 --> 00:31:36.540
It's because banks forgot why they existed in the first place.

293
00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:38.380
They lost their sense of purpose.

294
00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:40.960
I just talked about, I think we're very clear on our sense of purpose.

295
00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:47.860
We exist for the purpose of creating mutual prosperity in the form of positive social, environmental, cultural, and economic outcomes.

296
00:31:47.860 --> 00:31:49.300
That's what we do.

297
00:31:49.300 --> 00:32:03.020
The four major banks, or the investor owned banks, existed for the purpose of profit maximization and incentivizing executives to earn very large remuneration at the expense of their customer and their communities.

298
00:32:03.020 --> 00:32:04.760
That's why there was a Royal Commission.

299
00:32:04.780 --> 00:32:06.400
They forgot the sense of purpose.

300
00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:09.140
And we could kind of see it as a member of the ABA.

301
00:32:09.300 --> 00:32:16.840
We could see that there was a stark difference between our purpose and the purpose of the four major banks.

302
00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:22.100
And it's a great thing that the Royal Commission was called.

303
00:32:22.100 --> 00:32:22.980
Really great thing.

304
00:32:22.980 --> 00:32:23.900
I think that the...

305
00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:37.160
I have to give credit to the banks that were either part of the process or as in terms of more than being called to present or at least invest under.

306
00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:39.620
But I think the penny has dropped with these guys.

307
00:32:39.620 --> 00:32:41.920
And people say, I don't get sitting around and then be on change.

308
00:32:41.980 --> 00:32:43.020
I actually think that it will.

309
00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:52.780
From what I see, I think the Royal Commission and other businesses like us that can demonstrate that you can be a successful business by being a purpose-led and values-based business.

310
00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:56.460
We will influence the way other businesses operate.

311
00:32:56.460 --> 00:32:58.460
And those guys have learned the lesson.

312
00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:10.140
Those guys have learned the lesson that whilst they have to be profitable as we do, there has to be a way so they cannot trade off their social license for why they exist.

313
00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:13.700
And proof will be in the pudding and time to tell and everything else.

314
00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:24.520
But I sense that there is a much stronger realization and now amongst the investor-owned banks in the country than there's ever been before.

315
00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:27.420
Which does, I guess, create a challenge for us too.

316
00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:35.620
One of the things that we say in Bank australia is that we have a responsibility to continually raise the bar for responsible banking.

317
00:33:35.620 --> 00:33:50.460
And if the Royal Commission has any positive impact, it will change the behaviors that occur within investor-owned banks in the country, which means that we need to raise the bar higher in order to be able to demonstrate that there are other things that banks can do.

318
00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:57.240
There are other responsibilities and roles and purposes the banks can deliver.

319
00:33:57.240 --> 00:33:57.820
That's our role.

320
00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:07.840
But I do take some pride, I think, as everybody in the mutual banking sector should, that we weren't part of that process.

321
00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:10.679
It wasn't called because of anything we were doing wrong.

322
00:34:12.440 --> 00:34:14.139
Right.

323
00:34:14.139 --> 00:34:23.260
When we, Basil and I kind of caught up for coffee a couple of times, I got to understand Basil and what makes Basil tick and his background.

324
00:34:23.260 --> 00:34:25.760
I thought I would ask him a couple of questions too.

325
00:34:27.820 --> 00:34:35.960
So, the first one that I wanted to ask you, Basil, was around the pursuit of profit without purpose.

326
00:34:35.960 --> 00:34:41.380
So I kind of talked about we have a purpose, what's a profitable profit maximization is not our purpose.

327
00:34:41.380 --> 00:34:46.980
So I want to ask Basil, the pursuit of profit without purpose assumes a couple of things.

328
00:34:46.980 --> 00:35:01.660
It assumes that the point of life is to maximize financial wealth, that we as individuals live in an adversarial world and that this situation is inevitable.

329
00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:09.800
And I wanted to put to Basil, we see these ideas as modern day truths, many of us, perhaps not us, but others do.

330
00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:14.980
More so, ours, others default position.

331
00:35:14.980 --> 00:35:22.900
So is it right that profit maximization is a default position?

332
00:35:22.900 --> 00:35:24.540
And is that okay?

333
00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:29.100
Well, I don't think it is okay.

334
00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:31.240
That's from where I'm coming from.

335
00:35:31.240 --> 00:35:37.500
And I think that the pursuit of wealth for the sake of wealth in my book is obscene.

336
00:35:38.980 --> 00:35:43.260
because you just basically, and I know people who do that.

337
00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:59.740
So it's another thing saying I need a legitimate income to live on, but to pursue wealth for the sake of wealth and seek, totally identify with that and all that matters is to me, a most dehumanized human being.

338
00:36:00.620 --> 00:36:12.020
They might sound very good in terms of saying whether they drive what sort of car or have a mansion, blah, blah, blah, or throw a party for $21 million.

339
00:36:14.920 --> 00:36:17.120
I personally have never been impressed by that.

340
00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:29.340
I just thought it was so pathetic when I see so many people who are struggling just to live, to live like in Melbourne.

341
00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:35.500
I mean, I'm always left with an existential issue when I see a homeless person.

342
00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:45.080
Often, I'm left with a sense by saying, here I am in this country, supposed to be wealthy, and here we have homeless people.

343
00:36:45.160 --> 00:37:02.720
Yet I also know there are people who are concerned about it, but I've been involved with that and it's like knocking your head on a brick wall, because you find that really a lot of the development are actually in the hands of the developers and they're into social housing, which I'm not against.

344
00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:06.460
But if you bring up the notion of homelessness, they run a mile.

345
00:37:06.460 --> 00:37:09.080
They just don't want to hear you.

346
00:37:09.080 --> 00:37:18.240
It sort of reminds me going back in the 60s, this is it, tells you how old I am.

347
00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:26.860
It goes back to the 60s, is I can remember when we talked about indigenous issues, very few people actually even considered it.

348
00:37:26.860 --> 00:37:31.400
At least now you have a discourse in society.

349
00:37:31.400 --> 00:37:33.000
So there are ghosts.

350
00:37:34.080 --> 00:37:44.420
I like to sort of think that the sense of there's something, I am diminished when I know another human being is diminished.

351
00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:50.740
The existential issue for me is, am I a part of this as well?

352
00:37:50.740 --> 00:37:54.800
because I have a reasonable accommodation.

353
00:37:54.800 --> 00:38:02.320
I think I've shared this with friends of mine, like even when I went to Kenya, or even to Moleste, you go to a hotel, you stay in a hotel, and it's wonderful.

354
00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:09.940
I enjoy the accommodation, I enjoy the food, I enjoy the company, I enjoy the conversation, I enjoy the wine, I enjoy the food.

355
00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:18.100
And yet, when I went to bed, I was aware of the fact that there were hundreds of people who did not even have a bed.

356
00:38:18.100 --> 00:38:20.040
Now, what does that mean?

357
00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:25.780
Does that mean I have to be out there in the streets without a bed?

358
00:38:25.780 --> 00:38:26.860
No, I couldn't do that.

359
00:38:26.860 --> 00:38:31.740
Although I had a friend of mine who did precisely that and he died with them.

360
00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:38.120
I don't think I am that virtuous or call to such courage.

361
00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:39.280
I just don't have that.

362
00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:45.860
But I think it is incumbent on us to think about, take something like homelessness.

363
00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:47.660
I think we have some very good models.

364
00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:50.420
I mean, I talk about the Finnish model.

365
00:38:50.420 --> 00:38:52.460
They have actually sorted it out.

366
00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:58.060
Whenever I talk to groups concerned with homelessness, they say about things like, oh, it's all the drug addiction.

367
00:38:58.060 --> 00:38:58.480
True.

368
00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:00.060
It's all the sort of abuse they've had.

369
00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:00.720
True.

370
00:39:00.720 --> 00:39:03.000
You can have all this therapeutic intervention.

371
00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:08.620
But I say, for goodness sake, have a roof over their head first.

372
00:39:08.620 --> 00:39:16.340
Then you can bring in all the notion of how to make them feel comfortable or wanted or loved, whatever term you want to use.

373
00:39:17.420 --> 00:39:26.060
Now, the reason I suppose I think social banking, I don't know whether you're taking homelessness on.

374
00:39:26.180 --> 00:39:27.180
We go.

375
00:39:27.180 --> 00:39:28.700
There you are.

376
00:39:28.700 --> 00:39:29.520
He does.

377
00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.480
So that's good news.

378
00:39:31.480 --> 00:39:35.540
Now, what I also wanted to share is that I think you mentioned about culture.

379
00:39:35.540 --> 00:39:37.040
We must have mentioned about culture.

380
00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:51.860
I think what's happened to us is that there's always been a tension between my individualism and how I relate to others.

381
00:39:52.860 --> 00:39:57.000
I think that's been a perennial story, at least in the West.

382
00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:01.600
And I suspect also in the East, but we sort of culturally do it differently.

383
00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:11.740
And I think what's happened now is that apart from that, we also become more and more commodified in the way we engage in the world.

384
00:40:11.740 --> 00:40:16.600
That even good acts are seen in monetary terms.

385
00:40:16.600 --> 00:40:24.760
So we have even lost a sense, like altruism, it's sort of airbrushed.

386
00:40:24.760 --> 00:40:28.420
It's like it doesn't exist.

387
00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:33.800
And you can have some very good sophisticated arguments to say it doesn't exist.

388
00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:48.920
And so I'm not suggesting in any ways that I have the solutions, but I would like to think we should look at how we actually become human in this process of being connected.

389
00:40:49.520 --> 00:40:58.120
I know from experience that whenever I experience a disconnect, I experience a pain.

390
00:40:58.120 --> 00:41:04.280
And whenever I experience a connectedness, I experience a joy.

391
00:41:04.280 --> 00:41:09.940
Now, we can talk about that very much in terms of individuals and individual attributions.

392
00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:13.940
So for example, years and years I used to talk about poverty.

393
00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:22.920
And, you know, you could go back to absolute poverty, relative poverty, and poverty to quote Gandhi is a form of violence.

394
00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:50.740
But the real poverty is also to do with the poverty of the imagination, the poverty of living, the poverty of having a passion, the poverty of not being able to be sensitive to a poem, or not being able to enjoy a piece of theatre, or not being able to enjoy the magnificence of literature, or not being able to see the importance of art.

395
00:41:50.740 --> 00:41:55.640
And I think to do that, that's where I'd like to think good banking comes.

396
00:41:55.640 --> 00:42:02.860
It's actually got to have a certain level of material sustenance to be able to enjoy this.

397
00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:05.140
And I think life is meant to be enjoyed.

398
00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:12.560
I don't subscribe to the theory that, you know, you've got to somehow have a painful existence.

399
00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:15.820
It doesn't mean that we don't experience pain.

400
00:42:15.820 --> 00:42:20.420
All of us in life, as we journey through life, experience a pain.

401
00:42:20.420 --> 00:42:23.180
And it could be a pain on a number of levels.

402
00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:27.040
Now, as Antony said, we'd like to go deeper into this.

403
00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:33.140
So, I'd like your sort of reflections on, I think you're doing a great service, incidentally.

404
00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:35.100
So, I'm not in any way trying to diminish it.

405
00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:53.780
But I'd like us to sort of think about, how do we go now from a local, just on that basis, I think the great thing about in the past, what I've known about, say, the 1800s of other corporates, it is geographically based.

406
00:42:53.780 --> 00:42:57.960
So, you had a community that was actually that knew each other.

407
00:42:57.960 --> 00:43:01.280
And then you had a community that actually cared for one another.

408
00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:05.700
We don't have that anymore, entirely, except for certain groups.

409
00:43:05.700 --> 00:43:10.280
Like, when I go and see my cousins in India, they have it.

410
00:43:11.640 --> 00:43:13.580
Or, all my uncles have passed away.

411
00:43:13.580 --> 00:43:17.060
They used to sort of just live next door.

412
00:43:17.060 --> 00:43:23.060
And then they used to talk, play cards, and then go home and talk about the village gossip.

413
00:43:23.060 --> 00:43:25.120
There was a sense of being connected.

414
00:43:25.380 --> 00:43:33.760
And I think one of the issues now in our life at the moment, and it's not surprising, I mean, the UK has got a ministry for loneliness.

415
00:43:37.080 --> 00:43:44.820
And I think that is one of the big aspects of our existence at the moment, although there are lots of people who are lonely.

416
00:43:44.820 --> 00:43:49.340
And then they try to fill in that loneliness with nonsense.

417
00:43:51.400 --> 00:43:55.840
You know, it's like, it's also been globalized in a way.

418
00:43:56.440 --> 00:43:58.980
So, can I give you some hope?

419
00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:00.520
Can I give you some hope and some optimism?

420
00:44:00.520 --> 00:44:01.760
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

421
00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:05.880
One of the two words that you used in your opening address, was your hope and optimism.

422
00:44:05.880 --> 00:44:18.860
But I think I suppose the older I become, I am optimistic because I meet a lot of young people who remind me of my youth.

423
00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:26.640
And they remind me of the passion I had when I was in my 20s.

424
00:44:26.640 --> 00:44:27.900
Yes.

425
00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:31.640
Now, but there is the other aspect too, is that they are a different world.

426
00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:32.380
I mean, they are savvy.

427
00:44:32.380 --> 00:44:36.580
I mean, I am technologically challenged, for example.

428
00:44:36.580 --> 00:44:40.120
That's the word I think you used now, technologically challenged.

429
00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:41.400
And I am technologically challenged.

430
00:44:41.400 --> 00:44:46.260
And I decided that I want to do something about this, but my attempts have been rather pathetic.

431
00:44:46.460 --> 00:44:52.040
But anyway, but it's a question of actually a role.

432
00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:55.300
I'd like to think there's a role for elders.

433
00:44:55.300 --> 00:44:58.260
That's one thing the indigenous community has.

434
00:44:58.260 --> 00:45:09.540
And I think we need circles of elders who affirm young people to get on with it, whatever it is, and we should be encouraging them.

435
00:45:10.160 --> 00:45:17.600
I mean, that's just one thing that I'm in a way doing with a lot of young men that I meet, because they're terrific.

436
00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:22.720
They're trying to be, they're trying to be a good husband or a lover or a friend.

437
00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:42.480
And at the same time, they want to not come across as being chauvinistic, and they don't want to be machismo, and it's complex, because at another level, they can't express their testosterone, because they're too scared, because the women will sort of accuse them of being horrible men.

438
00:45:43.780 --> 00:45:45.760
So, they hold that back.

439
00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:46.600
They hold that back.

440
00:45:46.600 --> 00:45:55.080
So, there's this sort of stylized type of politically correct living that irritates me.

441
00:45:55.080 --> 00:45:59.760
And all they latch onto, which is like, oh, how many glasses of wine did you have?

442
00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:02.260
Or how many cigarettes do you smoke?

443
00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:08.060
Or these are sort of individual things, which are not, say, I'm against smoking, or against...

444
00:46:08.060 --> 00:46:13.720
What I'm saying is, it's easy to latch onto things like that for people to feel virtuous.

445
00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:21.020
And I'd like to think that their virtue has to go at what I would call a systemic and structural level.

446
00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:27.260
And that's where we need good policy and we could implement as a policy.

447
00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:31.020
I don't want good policy because I've read policy papers gathering dust.

448
00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:33.920
What we need is people who can implement it.

449
00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:36.580
And I've got a lot of hope and optimism.

450
00:46:36.580 --> 00:46:37.720
I think that's possible.

451
00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:40.880
And I think I'm a troubled egg when it comes to technology as well.

452
00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:41.440
Oh, good.

453
00:46:41.440 --> 00:46:42.880
Okay.

454
00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:46.240
But I have great hope that technology is part of that.

455
00:46:46.420 --> 00:46:49.500
If I look at the community that's now being formed as the...

456
00:46:52.920 --> 00:46:55.440
I've used the term community, but I'm actually going to...

457
00:46:56.020 --> 00:46:59.440
I'm trying to shift that term at the moment to movement.

458
00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:01.460
And we were formed as Creative Unions.

459
00:47:01.460 --> 00:47:02.700
We were described as so.

460
00:47:02.700 --> 00:47:06.080
When I came into the industry, we were doing a movement.

461
00:47:06.080 --> 00:47:07.820
And a movement then became an industry.

462
00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:12.660
And I kind of want to take it back to being a movement, a movement for positive change.

463
00:47:12.660 --> 00:47:16.300
The opportunity to actually create a movement is there through technology.

464
00:47:16.300 --> 00:47:18.500
And I see that every day in social media.

465
00:47:18.580 --> 00:47:30.200
I get this report on my desk every morning, which is the conversation that's occurring within social media around Bank australia and the positive things that people can do in the world with them in australia with their money.

466
00:47:30.200 --> 00:47:33.220
And there is a conversation that's occurring right now.

467
00:47:33.220 --> 00:47:52.160
If somebody is savvy enough to jump into Facebook or to Instagram or to Twitter, you'll probably see a conversation occurring somewhere in australia now around the role of money in society and the opportunity to create good in the world.

468
00:47:52.160 --> 00:48:13.620
So I'm actually very optimistic and have great hope that we can just rebalance the way that we see society and that we see the role of money by using technology to go back again to principles of movement creation.

469
00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:21.840
Go back to January, 4,000 people joined a bank because they wanted to create positive good in the world.

470
00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:23.200
So I'm very hopeful.

471
00:48:23.200 --> 00:48:32.540
It's then aligning that ambition that those people have for a better future through the way their money is invested to the issues that are important to them.

472
00:48:32.540 --> 00:48:37.880
And you touched on housing, and I think you touched on it, Antony, also on innovation in your opening comments.

473
00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:39.540
I'll give you an example of that.

474
00:48:39.540 --> 00:48:41.120
housing is critically important.

475
00:48:41.120 --> 00:48:42.880
I've always worked in the business of housing.

476
00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:46.420
I've built it, sold it, developed it, managed it, financed it.

477
00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:48.460
So housing has been core to my...

478
00:48:48.460 --> 00:48:53.100
I fundamentally believe that security of tenure provides better quality outcomes.

479
00:48:53.100 --> 00:48:54.000
It doesn't have to be...

480
00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:55.320
don't have to own it, you can lease it.

481
00:48:55.320 --> 00:49:04.440
But as long as you've got security of tenure, the evidence now, I believe, demonstrates that you have better social outcomes, economic outcomes, health outcomes, education outcomes.

482
00:49:04.440 --> 00:49:06.900
Security of tenure delivers quality of living.

483
00:49:07.980 --> 00:49:15.080
We, and the opportunity that we have through the Co-operative model is to test some new models.

484
00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:27.120
Let me tell you about some models that the Co-operative model enables you to attest, because we're not chasing profit maximization, we're not chasing shareholder return, we're trying to build value, wealth in different ways.

485
00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:44.700
Today, I had a most amazing conversation with my Impact Finance Manager around opportunities to invest in housing, house ownership for indigenous australians in partnership with the indigenous business Association of business australia, indigenous business australia Government Department.

486
00:49:45.740 --> 00:49:49.200
One of the things that research now shows is you can rebuild trust.

487
00:49:49.200 --> 00:49:54.460
trust has been lost in a range of different institutions, you will know that, whether it's in churches, whether it's in government and the like.

488
00:49:54.960 --> 00:50:01.340
But you can actually help rebuild trust by way of partnership, and partnership comes naturally to cooperatives.

489
00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:08.500
Partnerships between government and business to respond to, find solutions to social, economic, cultural issues.

490
00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:14.740
So we're working now with indigenous business australia to find ways where we can provide housing to indigenous australians.

491
00:50:14.820 --> 00:50:22.200
We can finance that housing, and the IVA and the government can actually carry some of the credit risk on that.

492
00:50:22.200 --> 00:50:36.060
So all of a sudden we can provide unbankable indigenous australians the opportunity to buy housing in australia, because we approach the issue differently to the way the four major banks or an investor-owned bank, they look at the profit maximisation.

493
00:50:36.060 --> 00:50:38.880
We look at wealth through a different lens.

494
00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:45.460
Another example, we entered the community housing market here in Melbourne about a decade, about 12 years ago.

495
00:50:45.460 --> 00:50:49.200
No bank in the country would touch it.

496
00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:56.600
But the Rudd government started to provide opportunities for community housing organisations, associations to take debt on.

497
00:50:56.600 --> 00:50:58.980
They weren't ready to take debt on.

498
00:50:58.980 --> 00:50:59.900
Their boards weren't ready.

499
00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:00.980
Their management weren't ready.

500
00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:10.960
We invested probably two years of time and effort in building the capability of boards and executive teams to understand how to take debt on so that it would become less of a credit risk to us.

501
00:51:11.620 --> 00:51:16.500
Again, the four major banks wouldn't do that because they were looking at quick profit maximisation.

502
00:51:16.500 --> 00:51:25.320
But the corporate model said there's a better long-term dividend that can be generated here for people and our own customers if we invest the time and effort.

503
00:51:25.320 --> 00:51:33.140
We did that to the point where we generated about $400 million worth of community housing investments across australia.

504
00:51:33.140 --> 00:51:51.220
It got to the point where the government, and this is okay, the government then introduced and or established an organisation called NIFIC, which enabled them to use the government guarantee to bring money in, to lend money to the community housing sector at a much lower price using their AAA credit rating versus our BBB plus credit rating.

505
00:51:51.220 --> 00:51:51.900
But guess what?

506
00:51:51.900 --> 00:52:01.540
It probably wouldn't have happened if the cooperative hadn't been there in the first building capacity, building capability, getting these guys to a point where they could take debt on the start to build scale.

507
00:52:01.540 --> 00:52:03.120
And it got way beyond the point.

508
00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:09.080
We've had a lot of that money refinanced out of that sector and the government's picked that up through through NIFIC.

509
00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:12.960
But now we've moved on to indigenous housing and then we'll move on to the next thing.

510
00:52:12.960 --> 00:52:18.200
And we will create markets and new opportunities because that's what a cooperative model can do.

511
00:52:18.200 --> 00:52:21.680
Cooperatives go into markets that don't work.

512
00:52:21.680 --> 00:52:24.440
They're broken markets and go, how can you fix this?

513
00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:33.280
How can you use the cooperative model, the cooperative principle, not based on profit maximization, but investing people's moneys in ways that create positive social environment?

514
00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:36.060
How can you find a business model to do that?

515
00:52:36.060 --> 00:52:40.960
We've just had a partnership with the Clean Energy Finance Corporation.

516
00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:48.160
Together with the Clean Energy Finance Corporation, we now provide the lowest cost home loan in australia, bar none.

517
00:52:48.160 --> 00:52:51.520
But the house has got to be sustainably designed.

518
00:52:51.520 --> 00:53:01.720
It's got to be one star beyond the statutory limit, which encourages people to build more sustainable design housing.

519
00:53:01.720 --> 00:53:08.700
We were the only financier that could sit down and have the discussion with NIFIC, because our purpose is different.

520
00:53:08.700 --> 00:53:17.780
Now, it will come to a point where that model is proven, and it will become of a scale that we can't do, and the four major banks will want to come in and start financing that business.

521
00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:21.740
Absolutely perfectly fine, because we seeded the market.

522
00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:23.120
And then we'll move on to the next thing.

523
00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:47.440
So, I've got great hope after all those years that we can redefine wealth, we can use innovation, and we can be hopeful and optimistic that in 2020 the Co-operative Model can still help find ways to create better quality outcomes, social, environmental, cultural, economic outcomes for people.

524
00:53:47.440 --> 00:53:48.920
Really, really hopeful.

525
00:53:48.920 --> 00:53:56.440
I'm a bit sad that I'm about to hit 60 and I'm going to go and retire, because there's so much time and so much opportunity in front of us that can still do good.

526
00:53:56.440 --> 00:53:57.700
Yeah, but don't retire.

527
00:53:57.700 --> 00:53:59.860
There's lots of things to do.

528
00:53:59.860 --> 00:54:09.640
I'm going to go to Italy, as you know, and live in a community which is a very strong community in the village where I have a home, which is really built on a cooperative economy.

529
00:54:11.220 --> 00:54:13.740
I think Antony is here.

530
00:54:13.740 --> 00:54:22.520
I hate to break into this conversation, but I would like to give anyone here present an opportunity to ask a question.

531
00:54:22.520 --> 00:54:28.140
because this is a dialogue, you can ask a question to Basil or you can ask a question to Rowan.

532
00:54:28.540 --> 00:54:33.380
Now, Sonia actually has a rosing mic here and we have our first hand up there.

533
00:54:33.380 --> 00:54:39.320
So, we'll probably take two or three questions and then take a little bit from there.

534
00:54:39.320 --> 00:54:42.220
Hi Rowan, I'm changing banks tomorrow.

535
00:54:45.480 --> 00:54:52.880
I feel like a lot of us aren't very good at teaching our kids financial literacy and schools are very good at either.

536
00:54:53.620 --> 00:54:58.440
Even people who like know what they're doing in their own lives don't do a very good job.

537
00:54:58.440 --> 00:55:02.160
They don't even do anything about teaching their kids financial literacy.

538
00:55:02.160 --> 00:55:14.620
So, is there an opportunity to have a bank for kids or some kind of separate program that really targets kids and encourages them to save and inspires them to be financially independent?

539
00:55:14.620 --> 00:55:15.660
That's a very hard.

540
00:55:15.660 --> 00:55:16.560
A bank for kids.

541
00:55:18.020 --> 00:55:22.140
Well, a friend of mine wanted to do that, but she didn't end up being out to do it because she got sick.

542
00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:23.040
Really?

543
00:55:23.040 --> 00:55:24.600
You know, it's been a frustration.

544
00:55:24.600 --> 00:55:31.620
I think the Co-operative Movement, the Mutual Banking Movement in australia has done some really, really cool things.

545
00:55:31.620 --> 00:55:33.920
But it's missed some amazing opportunities along the way too.

546
00:55:34.360 --> 00:55:39.040
You know, the fact that the Dolomites Commonwealth Bank got in, and it was very clever.

547
00:55:39.040 --> 00:55:45.180
And you probably saw that it's been accused of grooming kids in a nice possible way.

548
00:55:45.180 --> 00:55:48.440
But they were very clever and very shrewd the way they did it.

549
00:55:48.440 --> 00:55:50.280
They paid the schools.

550
00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:51.680
Schools are always looking for money.

551
00:55:51.680 --> 00:55:54.920
So the Commonwealth Bank paid the schools for every account that they opened.

552
00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:59.120
And as a consequence of that, many of you probably had Dolomite accounts.

553
00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:00.060
And it's amazing.

554
00:56:00.080 --> 00:56:01.920
Everybody had a Dolomite.

555
00:56:01.920 --> 00:56:04.760
The penetration was amazing.

556
00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:10.880
So I hope that we've got to burn that, right?

557
00:56:10.900 --> 00:56:17.480
I hope that through the hope and the optimism and the things that we're talking about, re-educating people about the role of money in society.

558
00:56:18.280 --> 00:56:26.240
I mean, I've sent in so many of focus groups over the years where you talk to people about, here's the question that we often ask people in australia.

559
00:56:26.240 --> 00:56:28.400
What does a bank do with your money?

560
00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:32.360
And I've had people say they put it in a safe.

561
00:56:35.560 --> 00:56:40.520
And then you ask, or the researcher says, and then, so when you go in and do a withdrawal, what do you think happens?

562
00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:42.620
And they say, well, they take it out of the safe.

563
00:56:43.880 --> 00:56:50.320
But the level of financial literacy in this country is beyond belief, is so low.

564
00:56:50.320 --> 00:56:53.440
People do not understand what banks do with their money.

565
00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:59.640
And part of our campaigning at the moment is to demonstrate that banks do some good things and they do some bad things.

566
00:56:59.640 --> 00:57:04.560
So if you don't want your money financing fossil fuels in the country, don't bank with the full major banks.

567
00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:13.120
If you don't want your money financing live export trade in australia, or tobacco or gambling or weapons and things, don't bank with the full major banks.

568
00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:21.700
So I'm hoping that we're trying to seed a process of educating australians around the role of money.

569
00:57:22.860 --> 00:57:27.420
My strategy to do that, my long-term plan is actually not to start with the kids.

570
00:57:27.420 --> 00:57:34.940
It's to try to get the adults, the parents to understand that the power of money and get them to educate their kids.

571
00:57:34.940 --> 00:57:46.500
Now we went out to our customers at the beginning of the year and said to them, we do this every year, who'd like to be the face of Bank australia in 2020?

572
00:57:46.500 --> 00:57:48.900
You can imagine any other bank asking that question.

573
00:57:48.900 --> 00:57:50.040
Like nobody would ever respond.

574
00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:53.840
Who'd want to be the face of NAB or Combank?

575
00:57:53.840 --> 00:57:55.840
Like you'd get nothing back.

576
00:57:55.840 --> 00:57:59.860
So we put that out and we've got to shut it down within 12 hours because we just get overwhelmed.

577
00:57:59.860 --> 00:58:02.020
So within 12 hours we're 160 people.

578
00:58:02.120 --> 00:58:11.260
Not only say they want to be the face of Bank australia, but they gave us their story and the amazing things that they're doing in their life and the pictures and the whole thing.

579
00:58:11.260 --> 00:58:21.260
About number three that came in was a five year old who said, I put my pocket money with Bank australia because I want to save the animals.

580
00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:30.600
So he becomes one of the faces of Bank australia and we will tell those stories out across the country.

581
00:58:30.820 --> 00:58:40.460
And I'm hoping that my five year old is telling the stories around the role of money is as powerful as an adult telling the story about the role of money and getting to the younger kids.

582
00:58:40.460 --> 00:58:53.600
But our average age, one of the things that we were running a risk of in terms of the business back in the early 90s when we said we could have changed, we could have do some stuff, we were going to fall off a cliff around age and customer base.

583
00:58:53.600 --> 00:59:03.340
And if we had not made a change, we would have, we would have had a whole bunch of older customers, long standing older customers, they were all big depositors, nobody borrowing, the business would not be sustainable.

584
00:59:03.340 --> 00:59:07.160
So over the years, we've driven down the average age of customer.

585
00:59:07.160 --> 00:59:16.160
So that 34 average age in January 30, the average age, we're probably the only bank in the country where the average age of customer is coming down.

586
00:59:18.460 --> 00:59:23.740
And it's coming down because people hope, optimism, the role of money in the society.

587
00:59:23.740 --> 00:59:26.800
So will I get to the point where it's a bank for kids?

588
00:59:26.800 --> 00:59:29.340
I'll probably won't get to the point where they're all kids.

589
00:59:29.760 --> 00:59:33.780
But getting younger kids is really, really important.

590
00:59:36.100 --> 00:59:37.960
Question over there, somewhere.

591
00:59:37.960 --> 00:59:40.380
Sonya, I'll get you to choose because there's lots of hands up.

592
00:59:40.380 --> 00:59:41.860
We'll probably take two more questions.

593
00:59:41.860 --> 00:59:44.300
Well, I'll try and be short so you can.

594
00:59:44.320 --> 00:59:48.580
I borrowed some years back $75,000 from the Credit Union.

595
00:59:48.580 --> 00:59:53.460
Actually, it's now part of CUA, Credit Union australia, but it wasn't there.

596
00:59:53.460 --> 01:00:00.040
And I moved a house on a small piece of fair land, 52 by 18 meters.

597
01:00:00.040 --> 01:00:03.440
I moved an existing house that was going to be demolished.

598
01:00:03.440 --> 01:00:06.040
No bank would have given me that money at all.

599
01:00:06.040 --> 01:00:08.700
And I got the permit from the local council.

600
01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:10.060
I don't know how I got it.

601
01:00:10.060 --> 01:00:17.620
And that was turning to three separate well-built units for clients of Kildonan.

602
01:00:17.640 --> 01:00:18.140
All right.

603
01:00:19.020 --> 01:00:19.440
Yeah.

604
01:00:19.440 --> 01:00:21.420
Okay.

605
01:00:21.420 --> 01:00:22.720
It was such a small thing.

606
01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:25.460
I mean, you can't even say it's a model to copy because it's one.

607
01:00:26.220 --> 01:00:30.840
But without the money with the credit union, it took me five years to pay it back.

608
01:00:31.900 --> 01:00:33.880
I couldn't have done it.

609
01:00:33.880 --> 01:00:36.700
I've been with the credit union for 35 years now.

610
01:00:37.120 --> 01:00:38.840
And so have my children.

611
01:00:38.840 --> 01:00:44.320
And the living and learning center around for 25 years, no longer, but I did then.

612
01:00:45.500 --> 01:00:51.060
Everyone in there working or many of the students were banking with some credit union.

613
01:00:51.060 --> 01:00:52.320
just copy that.

614
01:00:52.320 --> 01:00:54.280
You don't have to do much effort.

615
01:00:54.280 --> 01:01:06.580
And recently, Brother Wilson Lawrence in the monthly lunches had two people from, actually one of them was Trent Hall, to talk about cooperatives.

616
01:01:06.900 --> 01:01:10.920
And I would like you to keep them in mind, to invite them perhaps again.

617
01:01:10.920 --> 01:01:12.880
I mean, one of them was from the CFMEU.

618
01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:15.380
He's a lovely, lovely big guy.

619
01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:19.100
You never know, he's really muscle, you could ask him.

620
01:01:19.100 --> 01:01:21.960
But he's working on cooperatives.

621
01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:24.880
And I think we need to spread that kind of knowledge.

622
01:01:26.740 --> 01:01:32.140
I'll take that as a comment, Ivana, because we've got to, as Tony Jones says, take one from...

623
01:01:33.100 --> 01:01:34.360
Yes, sorry.

624
01:01:34.360 --> 01:01:37.020
You still have your question?

625
01:01:37.020 --> 01:01:39.220
My question's too big, go ahead.

626
01:01:42.820 --> 01:01:44.680
Is that last question, or?

627
01:01:44.700 --> 01:01:47.460
One here and then one there.

628
01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:48.420
Thank you, Rowan.

629
01:01:48.420 --> 01:01:55.440
Sorry, Basil, but Rowan, you mentioned about credit unions losing their way and banks losing their way.

630
01:01:55.440 --> 01:01:59.300
It's wonderful what's happening with Bank australia and credit unions.

631
01:01:59.820 --> 01:02:06.560
What's in, in, in process there to ensure that it retains its purpose?

632
01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:11.940
My work in other institutions that are value based, that's the issue.

633
01:02:11.940 --> 01:02:17.060
How do you ensure the sustainability in the future of that?

634
01:02:17.060 --> 01:02:19.320
I think there's a couple of ways.

635
01:02:19.320 --> 01:02:25.460
There's, and let me give you two, two, two answers.

636
01:02:25.460 --> 01:02:30.600
The first is to continually prove that the business model is successful, that it works.

637
01:02:30.600 --> 01:02:43.560
Now when I, I remember when I fronted up to the board in 20, in 2002 and said we're going to take a different direction, no longer jobs in geography, no longer teachers and scientists, attitudes and values, just trust me.

638
01:02:43.560 --> 01:02:44.200
But when you the...

639
01:02:46.660 --> 01:02:50.200
The board at that time said, what's the evidence?

640
01:02:50.200 --> 01:02:56.820
And I said, I can't give you any, just trust me, trust the science, trust the evidence that we've done.

641
01:02:56.820 --> 01:03:21.160
So part of it is good governance and a board that is, the founders that Antony referred to at the beginning, and I've read that paragraph out to our own board, good governance, being bold and being brave, and sitting around that board for all the right reasons, not the wrong reasons, that's part of good governance, a strong sense of purpose and that recognized in your constitution and the like, very, very clear.

642
01:03:21.160 --> 01:03:23.940
So good governance will hold it true.

643
01:03:23.940 --> 01:03:38.760
Another element of that is being able to measure and measure the performance of the business, not on profit maximization, but on impact, correct, how the values are derived, delivering wealth defined differently, value defined differently.

644
01:03:38.760 --> 01:03:44.100
So we will become, you might have heard B Corp, we will become a B Corp in australia.

645
01:03:44.100 --> 01:03:55.200
A purpose based business, a purpose led business, with a really, really strong sense, there were criteria around measurement in terms of community, in terms of environmental impact, in terms of governance, in terms of workforce.

646
01:03:55.200 --> 01:04:06.700
So building systems into the business that actually provide the level of discipline that's required to ensure that this is part of the DNA of the organization is critically, critically important.

647
01:04:06.700 --> 01:04:14.640
But at the end of the day, why is it, why don't you, once I leave, once I leave, how do we keep it going?

648
01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:23.280
Part of my process, the last five years really has been making sure that we really got good leadership transition in place, transition program and succession in place.

649
01:04:23.280 --> 01:04:27.060
So I've got my replacement all lined up.

650
01:04:27.060 --> 01:04:30.880
Fiona Nixon is sitting there already going.

651
01:04:30.880 --> 01:04:34.500
And that's a process of recognizing that we won't be here forever, clearly.

652
01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:44.620
But at least make sure that we've got people who share the same principles and values and experiences that are standing right next to us, that can step into those roles when we step away.

653
01:04:44.620 --> 01:04:57.340
And I joke with the guys and joke with Fiona, that now I'm going to sit in my little village over in Italy and just be amazed at the incredible things that they will have achieved when I've stepped away because they're cleverer than I will ever be.

654
01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:04.480
They will do things that I will just, I could never even imagine, because we've put that in place.

655
01:05:04.480 --> 01:05:18.180
So good governance, good processes, systems that measure and report on the things that are important and good succession plan is my, the approach that I've taken to say this can't change.

656
01:05:25.240 --> 01:05:32.620
Oh, I should say, there's no, there's no, there's not a conversation in the business.

657
01:05:32.620 --> 01:05:34.300
And we're going into board planning at the moment.

658
01:05:34.300 --> 01:05:40.100
There's not a single conversation in the business of saying, we should do anything different.

659
01:05:40.100 --> 01:05:45.720
No, no, I'm not saying that, but we've seen lots of institutions have lost their way.

660
01:05:45.720 --> 01:05:48.500
Yeah, and we did, we've been there, we did that in the late 90s.

661
01:05:48.560 --> 01:05:51.080
So, then it becomes so critical.

662
01:05:51.740 --> 01:05:55.200
What structures and processes do we put in place there?

663
01:05:55.480 --> 01:05:57.160
It tries to minimize it.

664
01:05:57.160 --> 01:05:58.300
Yeah, correct.

665
01:05:58.300 --> 01:06:02.480
Yeah.

666
01:06:02.480 --> 01:06:08.900
Yes, I was very impressed by your objective of trying to redefine wealth.

667
01:06:08.960 --> 01:06:11.620
I think that's what you said, wasn't it?

668
01:06:11.660 --> 01:06:14.860
It seems to me this is the important thing to do.

669
01:06:14.860 --> 01:06:33.980
And I wonder if you have any opinions or observations about anything that is taught currently in schools or universities about economics and what they say about the Co-operative and the credit union sector because, you know, it seems to me that it's almost non-existent.

670
01:06:34.620 --> 01:06:35.920
It's almost invisible.

671
01:06:36.240 --> 01:06:42.080
And that this idea of changing the concepts through education would be a tough thing to do.

672
01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:42.440
Yeah.

673
01:06:42.440 --> 01:06:49.260
No, we've said, I was saying to Basil, beginning of this being, something that, and Antony will remember, is something that we did in 2012.

674
01:06:49.260 --> 01:06:52.220
In 2012 was the International Year of the Co-operative.

675
01:06:52.260 --> 01:06:57.940
And at the end of the International Year of the Co-operative, and I think Melina is coming on to speak at one of these events, Melina Morrison.

676
01:06:57.940 --> 01:07:01.180
She and I were working on the International Year of the Co-operative in 2012.

677
01:07:01.180 --> 01:07:03.220
And we said at the end of this, there's got to be a legacy.

678
01:07:03.220 --> 01:07:04.420
What do we do after this?

679
01:07:04.420 --> 01:07:04.740
Don't know.

680
01:07:04.740 --> 01:07:06.260
It wasn't just a year and then you forget it.

681
01:07:06.720 --> 01:07:07.260
What do we do?

682
01:07:07.260 --> 01:07:14.340
So we, in the guideline name, Greg Walton, Melina Morrison and I said, we're going to establish the business Council for Co-operatives and Mutuals.

683
01:07:14.340 --> 01:07:26.380
We're going to have a business council that represents all Co-operatives and Mutuals, whether they're farming, dairy, whether they're financial, whether they're health insurance, whether they're roadside, Co-operatives and Mutuals in the country.

684
01:07:26.380 --> 01:07:31.380
And then we defined, well, if you set that up, what are some of the things that we're going to try and achieve?

685
01:07:32.240 --> 01:07:44.720
I was staggered that in australia, you could complete an MBA and you had no comp set, no awareness whatsoever of other business models, other than pretty much our partnership, the investor owned.

686
01:07:44.720 --> 01:07:50.620
But Co-operatives and Mutuals were not in the curriculum on any MBA anywhere in the country in 2012.

687
01:07:50.620 --> 01:07:51.920
I'm advised that they are now.

688
01:07:53.340 --> 01:07:54.660
Not in every one, but they are.

689
01:07:54.660 --> 01:07:59.080
You can now complete an MBA on Co-operative and Mutual Enterprise business.

690
01:07:59.080 --> 01:08:07.900
I remember sitting at a panel here in Melbourne, with one of the very large law firms, very, very large law firms in Melbourne.

691
01:08:07.900 --> 01:08:10.580
I won't say who it was because I'm embarrassed by saying it.

692
01:08:10.580 --> 01:08:11.560
But the guy was really nice.

693
01:08:11.560 --> 01:08:13.920
He said, you're the Co-operative blogger.

694
01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:15.240
I said, I'm coming to here.

695
01:08:15.240 --> 01:08:16.160
I'm talking about Co-operative.

696
01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:28.000
I said, as a courtesy, I'll let you know, I advise all my clients not ever to form a Co-operative or a Mutual.

697
01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:29.300
seriously?

698
01:08:29.300 --> 01:08:31.120
Why would you do that?

699
01:08:31.120 --> 01:08:44.279
He goes, I always advise my clients to become a company under the Corporations Act, because that provides the best, the robust structure for a company.

700
01:08:44.279 --> 01:08:53.100
And I said to this guy, we're operated, we're a Mutual, but we operate under the Corporations Act.

701
01:08:53.100 --> 01:08:58.760
We're a company, a company limited by a shareholder vote.

702
01:08:59.140 --> 01:09:02.800
That's, we are, we operate under the Corps Act, and we're a Mutual.

703
01:09:02.800 --> 01:09:11.399
And now the Corps Act actually has been changed, through the business Council have changed the Corps Act, so it does recognise Mutual as a status within the Corporations Act, but then it didn't.

704
01:09:11.399 --> 01:09:12.680
But I said, we're a company.

705
01:09:12.680 --> 01:09:15.359
So I don't know why you would even say that.

706
01:09:15.359 --> 01:09:32.859
So when we got up onto the panel, and we're talking about different ownership models, I said, you know what, folks, there's even lawyers in this city that would advise people not to become a Co-operative because they don't even know that we exist under the Corporations Act.

707
01:09:34.260 --> 01:09:36.800
That level of ignorance is beyond belief.

708
01:09:36.800 --> 01:09:40.779
But the business council is starting to get that into the curriculum now.

709
01:09:40.779 --> 01:09:44.020
To get people to understand that cooperatives is a very valid form.

710
01:09:44.020 --> 01:09:45.779
Mutuals is a very valid form.

711
01:09:45.779 --> 01:09:48.060
And you can be a mutual that exists in the Corps Act.

712
01:09:48.060 --> 01:09:50.560
And the Corps Act now, we've got the legislation changed.

713
01:09:50.880 --> 01:09:54.980
The Corporations Act now says mutual, defines mutual.

714
01:09:54.980 --> 01:09:56.400
Mutual is never defined.

715
01:09:56.400 --> 01:10:02.100
The Corporations Act now states you can be a co-op, a company under the Corporations Act and a mutual.

716
01:10:02.100 --> 01:10:03.720
And this is the definition of mutual.

717
01:10:03.720 --> 01:10:04.200
It's there.

718
01:10:04.200 --> 01:10:05.040
It's done.

719
01:10:05.040 --> 01:10:08.120
So even the lawyers can't use that as an excuse anymore.

720
01:10:08.120 --> 01:10:09.440
It's there.

721
01:10:09.440 --> 01:10:11.140
Yeah.

722
01:10:13.280 --> 01:10:15.180
I feel sorry for this gentleman here.

723
01:10:15.180 --> 01:10:16.820
He said he had a very big question.

724
01:10:16.820 --> 01:10:17.820
So I'll put a challenge to you.

725
01:10:17.980 --> 01:10:23.660
If you can find the smallest part, most important part of that question, or I can wrap it up.

726
01:10:23.660 --> 01:10:24.400
Okay.

727
01:10:24.440 --> 01:10:47.900
How can we expand the mutual cooperative model fast because we have an infrastructure that's been built, that is a pyramid of growth, profit, growth, profit, and returns to shareholders?

728
01:10:47.920 --> 01:11:03.380
And how, I don't think that we're going to achieve the definition of the society that we want until we break that model?

729
01:11:03.400 --> 01:11:08.220
And what's a couple of good sledgehammers to try?

730
01:11:08.220 --> 01:11:09.440
There you go.

731
01:11:09.440 --> 01:11:10.180
So a couple of them.

732
01:11:10.180 --> 01:11:13.020
My first sledgehammer was the business Council Copies and Mutuals.

733
01:11:13.060 --> 01:11:14.940
Anthony mentioned a number before.

734
01:11:14.940 --> 01:11:21.680
About eight out of ten australians are actually members of a Co-operative Mutual member-owned organisation and don't even know it.

735
01:11:21.680 --> 01:11:28.220
So creating a sense of awareness that you are part of something that actually is around member ownership is really, really critically important.

736
01:11:28.280 --> 01:11:35.420
And that's part of the role of the business Council Copies and Mutuals, just to get it into the curriculum, work with government.

737
01:11:35.420 --> 01:11:47.280
So every party now has a Minister for Co-operatives and Mutuals, should have gone, a Minister with a responsibility for Co-operatives or Mutuals never existed before.

738
01:11:47.280 --> 01:11:49.680
So some of this is part of the process.

739
01:11:49.680 --> 01:12:02.080
But you know, I think that it's interesting, when we've got record customer acquisition now, they're not joining us because of our ownership model.

740
01:12:02.080 --> 01:12:07.220
They're not joining us because we're cooperative or mutual, they probably won't even know that.

741
01:12:07.220 --> 01:12:12.420
They're joining us because of a strong sense of purpose and values alignment.

742
01:12:12.420 --> 01:12:22.020
And I think that's probably, I can pretty much shut a conversation down instantly by talking about cooperative or mutual ownership structures.

743
01:12:23.460 --> 01:12:28.220
I can do it, I can get, I can put you into a hypnotic trance.

744
01:12:29.760 --> 01:12:42.320
But I think I would be able to engage you on a conversation around the role of money in society and how we can create better social, environmental, economic, cultural outcomes if we invest money differently.

745
01:12:42.320 --> 01:12:58.540
So we as a movement industry, I hope we will one day become a movement again, have to learn how to have the conversation with people using a language that resonates with them and they understand and they want to engage back with us.

746
01:12:58.540 --> 01:13:04.160
Unfortunately, a lot of us have used really as language that just shut people down.

747
01:13:04.160 --> 01:13:06.160
We've got to use a different language.

748
01:13:10.320 --> 01:13:13.440
Well, I think we've come to the end of the evening.

749
01:13:13.440 --> 01:13:15.620
So thank you for being here.

750
01:13:16.200 --> 01:13:23.160
And thank you, Rowan, because I think you've created a whole new client group here.

751
01:13:24.240 --> 01:13:26.880
And people are going to be quite committed to it.

752
01:13:26.900 --> 01:13:40.180
And all I wanted to say is that I really appreciate the fact that you've given away how people can actually use their money and to use it with purpose and meaning.

753
01:13:40.420 --> 01:13:42.820
And I think that's what we're...

754
01:13:42.820 --> 01:13:44.060
just one question I'll ask.

755
01:13:44.060 --> 01:13:46.760
You know, there's a great recruitment that you've got.

756
01:13:46.760 --> 01:13:49.220
I'm curious, it was huge numbers.

757
01:13:50.260 --> 01:13:51.840
Did they all...

758
01:13:51.840 --> 01:14:00.080
Did you get a sense to whether they actually were cooperating with others or was it just a very individualistic stance?

759
01:14:00.080 --> 01:14:01.180
It sounds like a Dorothy...

760
01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.420
Dorothy Dixon sounds like a Dorothy Dixon question.

761
01:14:05.420 --> 01:14:10.040
I don't know if I should finish on this or not, because we haven't discussed this before.

762
01:14:11.420 --> 01:14:29.120
Why I'm so confident, hopeful, that we can return to be a movement of people is that for every customer who joins the bank, they tell 11 other people that they've joined the bank, and they do so with great pride, which is amazing.

763
01:14:29.120 --> 01:14:39.620
There's no other bank in the country where people say, I've actually just shifted my banking to Bank australia, and they tell 11, that's their numbers, 11 other people.

764
01:14:39.620 --> 01:14:43.980
What was amazing when we went to them and said, okay, well, that sounds really good.

765
01:14:43.980 --> 01:14:46.440
Maybe we can encourage you to do more of that.

766
01:14:46.440 --> 01:14:48.440
What could we do?

767
01:14:48.440 --> 01:14:49.340
What do you need?

768
01:14:49.580 --> 01:14:51.820
What would you want as an incentive?

769
01:14:51.820 --> 01:14:53.060
What do we do?

770
01:14:53.060 --> 01:14:56.500
If could we incentivize you by giving you something?

771
01:14:56.500 --> 01:14:57.360
And they know what they said.

772
01:14:59.320 --> 01:15:02.000
If you did that, I'd stop doing it.

773
01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:03.940
We want nothing from you.

774
01:15:03.940 --> 01:15:04.820
Nothing.

775
01:15:04.820 --> 01:15:06.860
We're doing it out because we believe in it.

776
01:15:06.860 --> 01:15:07.840
So don't give us money.

777
01:15:07.840 --> 01:15:09.020
Don't give us give outs.

778
01:15:09.020 --> 01:15:11.140
There's nothing whatsoever.

779
01:15:11.140 --> 01:15:16.220
Give us nothing other than give us, make us proud to be a customer of the bank.

780
01:15:16.220 --> 01:15:19.920
And we will continue to tell people to switch their banking.

781
01:15:19.920 --> 01:15:25.280
That's why I'm so confident that we can rebuild the movement of people that brings about positive change.

782
01:15:25.420 --> 01:15:27.860
And that's what the Power of Co-operative Bonds is about.

783
01:15:27.860 --> 01:15:36.400
Well, that's great because I think it brings in line just with the sort of community development stuff that Antony and I have been involved with in the past.

784
01:15:37.960 --> 01:15:41.040
There's a thing which I call the Power of Five.

785
01:15:42.160 --> 01:15:51.800
And the Power of Five is this basically, if five people got together, they could actually harness another five each.

786
01:15:52.900 --> 01:16:12.140
So I was just thinking whether your bank could be an initiator to test ideas what people would like to do and to be able to start that movement that we both cherish.

787
01:16:12.140 --> 01:16:12.680
Absolutely.

788
01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:13.800
Let's talk.

789
01:16:13.800 --> 01:16:14.880
Let's talk.

790
01:16:14.880 --> 01:16:17.620
And I think that's a really good note to end on.

791
01:16:17.740 --> 01:16:24.120
And I would really like to thank both Basil and Rowan for being part of this conversation tonight.

792
01:16:28.480 --> 01:16:37.180
And why I think it's a good note to end on is that the legal minimum number to form a cooperative is, guess how many people?

793
01:16:38.280 --> 01:16:38.820
Five.

794
01:16:38.820 --> 01:16:40.400
Exactly.

795
01:16:40.400 --> 01:16:42.200
So you've hit the right number.

796
01:16:43.280 --> 01:16:46.120
So I'd really again like to thank both speakers.

797
01:16:46.120 --> 01:16:46.920
I've learnt a lot.

798
01:16:47.260 --> 01:16:48.360
I think we've gone into the history.

799
01:16:48.360 --> 01:16:50.800
I've learnt a lot about Bank australia.

800
01:16:50.820 --> 01:16:55.740
And I'd also like to recognize Craig who's here from APS Benefits.

801
01:16:55.740 --> 01:17:01.120
It's also a kind of a financial cooperative that I'm a member of personally.

802
01:17:01.120 --> 01:17:04.940
So it's great to have some other stakeholders in the audience.

803
01:17:04.940 --> 01:17:09.900
I'd really like to thank, this has been a new kind of thing that we're trying tonight.

804
01:17:09.900 --> 01:17:13.580
And I'd really like to thank Brian who's recorded tonight.

805
01:17:15.360 --> 01:17:20.580
And I would really like to thank Shannon who's been taking some photographs tonight.

806
01:17:20.580 --> 01:17:26.960
Both of these people are out there doing amazing art, doing kind of amazing things in the IT area.

807
01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:30.660
So have a chat to them afterwards.

808
01:17:30.660 --> 01:17:36.880
Now, we do have a little card here for Rowan.

809
01:17:36.880 --> 01:17:39.300
Now, in some ways it's quite sad.

810
01:17:39.300 --> 01:17:41.960
It's just a card, but it's not a big bottle of wine.

811
01:17:42.040 --> 01:17:43.840
It's not a bunch of flowers.

812
01:17:43.840 --> 01:17:46.720
But it is a card with a heartfelt message.

813
01:17:46.720 --> 01:17:53.640
And it's a card that is hand made, made in New Zealand, with sustainable ink and those kind of things.

814
01:17:53.640 --> 01:17:58.260
And the card features a circle of wise owls.

815
01:17:58.260 --> 01:18:03.700
So that's really what we're trying to achieve tonight, is getting a circle of wise owls.

816
01:18:03.700 --> 01:18:05.220
That includes you as well.

817
01:18:05.220 --> 01:18:06.680
So I'll just give you that, Rowan.

818
01:18:08.620 --> 01:18:10.140
Thank you, Rowan.

819
01:18:10.140 --> 01:18:16.700
And lastly, do we have some feathers for you?

820
01:18:16.700 --> 01:18:25.840
I'd like to thank Sonia, my board member in the Co-operative causeway, who will grab that little tankard of feathers.

821
01:18:25.840 --> 01:18:29.740
Now, what do you think these tankards represent?

822
01:18:30.780 --> 01:18:31.220
Any guesses?

823
01:18:33.740 --> 01:18:36.880
A drink on your way out.

824
01:18:36.880 --> 01:18:42.260
Grab a feather, head down to the bar, and thank you to Rowan and Bank australia for the generosity.

825
01:18:43.620 --> 01:18:44.680
Thank you very much for coming.